cff-version: 1.2.0
title: >-
  Apply, Don't Articulate: A Multi-Paradigm Study of Internal-Model
  Prompting in Large Language Models
message: >-
  If you use this work, please cite the v3 NeurIPS-format paper or the
  v2 detailed treatment as appropriate.
type: software
authors:
  - given-names: Mohamed A.
    family-names: Mabrok
    email: m.a.mabrok@gmail.com
repository-code: 'https://github.com/Minds-R-Lab/phase_margin_llm'
abstract: >-
  We test the practitioner reading of the Internal Model Principle of
  Francis and Wonham (1976) — "ask the LLM to articulate an internal
  model of its environment before acting" — across 16,000+ prompted
  trials in two distinct symbolic paradigms (deterministic integer
  sequence prediction and Python code debugging) and seven open-weight
  model scales (Qwen2.5 / Qwen2.5-Coder 7B/14B/32B; Llama3.1-70B-q4).
  Articulating an internal model never significantly helps; the
  IM-Hypothesis prompt collapses pass-rate by 97 percentage points at
  Qwen2.5-Coder-14B in code debugging, the largest single
  prompt-induced regression we are aware of. Four causal-mechanism arms
  refute the simplest tokenized-commitment account but support a
  sharper one: the harm is in rule-generation, not rule-application.
  Providing the rule directly (Oracle) helps with monotone scale on
  hard tasks, reaching an 84% asymptotic-error reduction at
  Qwen-32B-hard sequence prediction. We propose this as a clean
  cross-paradigm deployment principle: "maintain an internal model"
  prompts hurt; "apply this stated rule" prompts help.
keywords:
  - large language models
  - prompt engineering
  - chain-of-thought
  - internal model principle
  - control theory
  - code generation
  - sequence prediction
  - empirical evaluation
